<HEADLINE>
YANKEES PLAN TRIBUTES TO STEINBRENNER AND SHEPPARD
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As expected, the Yankees will hold a tribute to George
Steinbrenner before Friday night's game against the Tampa Bay Rays
at Yankee Stadium. The tribute will also honor the longtime Yankees
announcer Bob Sheppard, who died Sunday, just two days before
Steinbrenner died.
</P>
<P>
In a statement Thursday, the Yankees said that the pregame
ceremonies would include a video tribute to Steinbrenner and a
moment of silence honoring both men. The team urged fans to be in
their seats at 6:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
An Army sergeant will sing the national anthem, and there will
also be a West Point color guard.
</P>
<P>
The Yankees said a video tribute for Sheppard would take place
on Saturday, when the Yankees stage their annual Old-Timers' Day in
the Bronx, an event that will be attended by numerous former
Yankees who played for Steinbrenner over the decades.
</P>
<P>
The crowds at both games are likely to give long and loud
salutes to Steinbrenner, the longtime owner. Still, the Yankees are
also planning separate memorial services for him that will be held
at the stadium and at Steinbrenner Field in Tampa, Fla., the city
where Steinbrenner made his home. The dates for those memorial
services have not been set.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a private funeral for Steinbrenner was expected to be
held Saturday in Florida. Sheppard's funeral was held Thursday on
Long Island.
</P>
</TEXT>
