<DOC id="NYT_ENG_20100726.0101" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
TOM TANCREDO RUN A GOP GAME-CHANGER IN COLO. GOVERNOR ' S RACE
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Faced with two politically-damaged gubernatorial candidates and
the emergence of Tom Tancredo as a third-party contender who will
likely split the GOP vote, dejected Colorado Republicans Monday
tried to come up with a realistic strategy to take back the
governor's mansion.
</P>
<P>
But political observers -- and even GOP chair Dick Wadhams -- were
already predicting that former Congressman Tancredo's entry into
the race sounded the death knell for the party's gubernatorial bid
and may cause problems for state legislative races.
</P>
<P>
"It's difficult if not impossible to beat (Democrat) John
Hickenlooper with Tancredo in the race," said Wadhams, noting that
Tancredo will siphon just enough votes away from the GOP nominee to
give Hickenlooper a win.
</P>
<P>
Added political analyst Eric Sondermann: "There is a danger
that Tancredo is going to say outrageous things and other
Republicans will be called on to react to them. This complicates
the Republican agenda."
</P>
<P>
Tancredo, a former Colorado congressman, is perhaps most
well-known for his staunch opposition to illegal immigration. Most
recently, he has called for the impeachment of President Barack
Obama. Three years ago, he said the U.S. should "bomb Mecca."
</P>
<P>
Last week, he issued an ultimatum to Republican gubernatorial
candidates Scott McInnis, who is embroiled in a plagiarism scandal,
and Dan Maes, who owes $17,500 for violating campaign finance laws:
promise by Monday to get out of the race if polls show the Aug. 10
primary winner lagging behind Hickenlooper or else he would get in
as the American Constitution Party candidate.
</P>
<P>
Both McInnis and Maes rejected his ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
"Coming from a man whose career has been marked by
often-astonishing levels of arrogance, this move shouldn't surprise
us," Maes said. "And yet, one would suppose that even someone of
Tancredo's conceit would bow to the greater good in a year such as
this."
</P>
<P>
McInnis didn't address Tancredo specifically, but issued a
statement saying: "Those looking for a deadline should focus on
the only real deadline: August 10 at 7 p.m. This is when the polls
close, the people have voted and their votes are counted."
</P>
<P>
Tancredo said he intends to officially become the constitution
party candidate as soon as a number of legal requirements are
fulfilled. And he isn't bothered by those who call him a spoiler.
</P>
<P>
"Most of my political life, a lot of people have disliked what
I do," he said in an interview with The Denver Post, which first
reported Monday his intention to launch a third-party bid. "The
(Republican) party is already a mess."
</P>
<P>
Wadhams said that Tancredo's third-party candidacy had nothing
to do with Republicans and everything to do with Tacredo's
self-interest.
</P>
<P>
"He is a maniacal egotist whose only goal is to get media
attention," he said.
</P>
<P>
This year was the Republicans' best shot at winning the
governor's race in eight years, and a number of independent
political groups and the Republican Governor's Association had
already invested time and money in the race.
</P>
<P>
But there are 37 governor contests this year, and about 25 are
competitive, said Jennifer Duffy, who analyzes the country's
gubernatorial races as a senior editor at the non-partisan Cook
Political Report.
</P>
<P>
"There are a lot of mouths to feed," she said. "At some
point, the RGA is going to make a decision about who they can
realistically help or whether they are throwing money at a lost
cause."
</P>
<P>
The RGA did not return an email for comment.
</P>
<P>
Money from their group, as well as independent committees, help
not only the top candidates, but the ones down the ticket --
especially with get-out-the vote efforts. If funding dries up,
legislative candidates may face additional hurdles.
</P>
<P>
"With Tom Tancredo in the race, it makes it extremely
challenging for Republicans to have a successful November," said
Sean Tonner, who is involved with at least one group trying to
raise and spend millions of dollars to elect state Republicans.
Last week, the Post reported that McInnis' plagiarism scandal
negatively impacted Tonner's fundraising, making it difficult to
pay the bills.
</P>
<P>
Tancredo plans to leave McInnis and Maes alone and "solely
target Hickenlooper," said Tancredo spokeswoman Jennifer Raiffie.
Tancredo has criticized Hickenlooper in the past, notably when an
illegal immigrant who was a dishwasher at a restaurant owned in
part by Hickenlooper killed one Denver police officer and wounded
another. The employee had been stopped three previous times for
routine traffic incidents but Denver police and the courts let him
go when he produced a valid Mexican driver's license.
</P>
<P>
Tancredo can likely inflict political damage upon Hickenlooper,
but political observers don't believe it will be long-lasting,
especially since Tancredo is viewed as too far right by many
unaffiliateds and moderates.
</P>
<P>
"I think Tancredo can make Hickenlooper's life less pleasant,
but I would say what Colorado cares about is jobs and the
economy," said Katy Atkinson, a GOP consultant. "In the past when
Republicans have tried to make illegal immigration a singular wedge
issue, it hasn't worked."
</P>
<P>
In the 1992 presidential election, Colorado backed Democrat Bill
Clinton: independent candidate Ross Perot took 23 percent of the
vote, while President George H. Bush got 36 percent and Clinton
received 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
"A few weeks ago, every poll showed Republicans up an average
of five points because the election has become a referendum on
Obama," said Denver pollster Floyd Ciruli. "But there is no
possibility of a win in a three-way race with two Republicans."
</P>
</TEXT>
